       <header class="home-featured-item-header">
        <h1 class="home-featured-item-title">
         <a href="http://complit.berkeley.edu/featured/tim-hampton-on-the-humanities/" rel="bookmark" title="Permalink to Tim Hampton on the importance of an education in the Humanities">
          Tim Hampton on the importance of an education in the Humanities
         </a>
        </h1>
       </header>
       <!-- .entry-header -->
       <p>
        Comparative Literature Professor Tim Hampton, Director of the Townsend Center in the Humanities, writes about why
        <a href="http://blogs.berkeley.edu/2018/08/09/fake-news-and-humanities-education/">
         an education in the Humanities is essential in this time of Fake News.
        </a>
       </p>
      </article>
      <article class="group home-featured-item" id="post-17350">
       <header class="home-featured-item-header">
        <h1 class="home-featured-item-title">
         <a href="http://complit.berkeley.edu/featured/sawyer-seminar-dissertation-fellowship-announcement/" rel="bookmark" title="Permalink to Sawyer Seminar Working Group Invitation">
          Sawyer Seminar Working Group Invitation
         </a>
        </h1>
       </header>
       <!-- .entry-header -->
       <h4>
        Sawyer Seminar Working Group Invitation
       </h4>
       <div>
        Dear campus community:
       </div>
       <div>
       </div>
       <div>
        We would like to invite you to a multi-disciplinary working group in connection with the 2018-2019 UC Berkeley Sawyer Seminar on the topic of linguistic anthropology and literary and cultural study. You can find a longer description of the Seminar
        <a data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=http://complit.berkeley.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/SawyerDescription2018-v1.pdf&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1524759329729000&amp;usg=AFQjCNGP_sXcGRMXm8XlOxE5j54gM24Xew" href="http://complit.berkeley.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/SawyerDescription2018-v1.pdf" rel="noopener" target="_blank">
         here.
        </a>
        The working group will be meeting eight times throughout the year to discuss work from the Seminar’s invited speakers and others. The Sawyer Seminar itself will consist of seven two-day events across the academic year dedicated to a series of interlocking themes: translation / transduction, sound, publics, politics, religion, sexuality, or ethics. In addition to a meeting coinciding with each of these seven sessions, our first meeting will serve as something of an introduction to linguistic anthropology and its potential relations to literary and cultural study.
        <a class="more-link" href="http://complit.berkeley.edu/featured/sawyer-seminar-dissertation-fellowship-announcement/#more-17350">
         » Read on »
        </a>
       </div>
      </article>
     </article>
    </section>
   </section>
